            <thetext>Currently, the only way to get text of arbitrary length to consume its appropriate amount of horizontal and vertical space, and to reflow as the window changes sizes, is to use a qx.ui.basic.Label with the &#39;rich&#39; property set to true. Setting that property to true, however, is dangerous because it allows HTML injection attacks if the data being displayed comes from a user.

An interface to qx.ui.basic.Label to display reflowing text that is immune from HTML injection attack should be provided. The attached patch is a proof-of-concept which shows that it is possible. When the patch is applied, the demobrowser ui/LabelReflow demo properly reflows, but displays the embedded &lt;b&gt; tags as text instead of interpreting them as HTML.

Please provide a reasonable interface to qx.ui.basic.Label to allow preventing the call to element.innerHTML=value.</thetext>
          </long_desc>
